# PNG image borders (portfolio / web-main)

Match stroke colour to palette via `--image-border` (set on `transitionend` in `colorable-palette.js` — do not drive borders from interpolating `--page-text` inside `filter`).

## Rectangular PNG (UI mockups, screenshots, cards)

Use a **flat 3px ring** — cheap, smooth scroll, no `filter`:

```css
img {
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px var(--image-border, var(--page-text));
}
```

**Reference:** `web-main/css/nespresso-sandbox.css` — `.timeline-content img`, `.project-image--desktop img`.

## Peculiar / non-rectangular PNG (organic silhouettes, cut-out shapes)

Use **stacked `drop-shadow`** so the stroke hugs transparent alpha — apply to **few images only** (perf):

```css
img {
  filter:
    drop-shadow(1px 0 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(-1px 0 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(0 1px 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(0 -1px 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(2px 0 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(-2px 0 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(0 2px 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)))
    drop-shadow(0 -2px 0 var(--image-border, var(--page-text)));
}
```

**Reference:** `web-main/css/nespresso-sandbox.css` — `.project-image--mobile img` (bottom hero).

## Do not

- Put drop-shadow on every timeline image (scroll/reveal jank).
- Use viewport IO or per-frame filter toggling unless explicitly asked.
- Use `background-attachment: fixed` on timeline overlays over filtered images.
